Introduction

Bike share program is a common tool across cities allowing public access to bikes and/or electric bikes typically through temporary renting. First emerged in 1960s Europe, the first bike-sharing model was a political statement against pollution and cars in the city (Walker, 2018). In line with that spirit, today, with an increased emphasis on curbing GHG emission, multimodal mobility, and the equitable and health-related aspects of traveling, the regional bike-sharing system is becoming an increasingly popular tool among major U.S. cities like New York City, Philadelphia, Chicago, and Los Angeles (PBSC, 2022). Nonetheless, subjected to supply-demand interactions, the efficiency of bike-sharing systems and stations can be challenged by a variety of factors including weather conditions, time, and outages. How to predict the influential pattern of such factors is thus a critical concern of bike-share rebalancing.

The following project has picked Philadelphias Indego bike share as a case study to develop a predictive model to assist future rebalancing strategies. As of the end of 2023, Indego manages 2400 bikes and 250 stations (Rinde, 2024). However, please note that due to temporal restrictions imposed by the availability of American Community Survey data, the following report is produced based on Indego data between July 1 and July 31, 2022.

Acknowledging that bike rebalancing could be conducted physically (eg. through transporting bikes using truck fleets) or virtually (through provision of discounts, rewards, or other pricing incentives), the report incorporates time lag features suitable to inform both types of strategy. For instance, by accounting for lags in units of days preceding and post a national holiday, the tool will be able to assist collective relocation of bikes to stations where peak uses most likely occur. On the other hand, by accounting for lag features including number of trips in previous hour(s), the model could also potentially inform immediate, short-term pricing strategies.

Data Gathering

Bike Trips Data

First, we parsed each Indego bike share trip record in July, 2022 to identify its specific week of year and day of the week. Since the analysis is more concerned with rebalancing bikes to meet pick-up supply, only start time at which the trip is made is processed and rounded to the nearest hour and quarter.

dat <- read.csv("indego-trips-2022-q3/indego-trips-2022-q3.csv")

dat <- dat %>% 
  mutate(start_time = as.POSIXct(start_time, format = "%m/%d/%Y %H:%M"),
         end_time = as.POSIXct(end_time, format = "%m/%d/%Y %H:%M"))

#parsing data
dat2 <- dat %>%
  mutate(interval60 = floor_date(ymd_hms(start_time), unit = "hour"),
         interval15 = floor_date(ymd_hms(start_time), unit = "15 mins"),
         month = month(interval60),
         week = week(interval60),
         dotw = wday(interval60, label=TRUE)) %>% 
  filter(month == 7)

Weather Data

Then, using riem_measures, we loaded weather data from Philadelphia Airport (PHL), including hourly record of temperature, wind speed, precipitation over the study period. We also visualized the temporal patterns of various weather features (fig.1).

invisible(capture.output({
weather.Panel <- 
  riem_measures(station = "PHL", date_start = "2022-07-01", date_end = "2022-07-31")
}))

weather.Panel <- weather.Panel %>% 
  dplyr::select(valid, tmpf, p01i, sknt)%>%
  replace(is.na(.), 0) %>%
    mutate(interval60 = ymd_h(substr(valid,1,13))) %>%
    mutate(week = week(interval60),
           dotw = wday(interval60, label=TRUE)) %>%
    group_by(interval60) %>%
    summarize(Temperature = max(tmpf),
              Precipitation = sum(p01i),
              Wind_Speed = max(sknt)) %>%
    mutate(Temperature = ifelse(Temperature == 0, 42, Temperature))

#visualize weather data

grid.arrange(

Census Data

Census tract level data from ACS 2022 5-year estimates is retrieved and processed. Key features gathered include median household income, percent of working individuals taking public transportation, and percent of white individuals. While these data will not be directly applied in model building, we joined them to the rideshare data set to evaluate model performance later on.

invisible(capture.output({
PHLCensus <- 
  get_acs(geography = "tract", 
          variables = c("B01003_001", "B19013_001", 
                        "B02001_002", "B08013_001",
                        "B08012_001", "B08301_001", 
                        "B08301_010", "B01002_001"), 
          year = 2022, 
          state = "PA", 
          geometry = TRUE, 
          county= "Philadelphia",
          output = "wide") %>%
  rename(Total_Pop =  B01003_001E,
         Med_Inc = B19013_001E,
         Med_Age = B01002_001E,
         White_Pop = B02001_002E,
         Travel_Time = B08013_001E,
         Num_Commuters = B08012_001E,
         Means_of_Transport = B08301_001E,
         Total_Public_Trans = B08301_010E) %>%
  select(Total_Pop, Med_Inc, White_Pop, Travel_Time,
         Means_of_Transport, Total_Public_Trans,
         Med_Age,
         GEOID, geometry) %>%
  mutate(Percent_White = White_Pop / Total_Pop,
         Mean_Commute_Time = Travel_Time / Total_Public_Trans,
         Percent_Taking_Public_Trans = Total_Public_Trans / Means_of_Transport)

PHLTracts <- PHLCensus %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  distinct(GEOID, .keep_all = TRUE) %>%
  select(GEOID, geometry) %>% 
  st_sf() %>% 
  st_transform(crs = "EPSG:2272")

dat_census <- dat2 %>%
  filter(!is.na(start_lat) & !is.na(start_lon) 
         & !is.na(end_lat) & !is.na(end_lon)) %>%
  st_as_sf(coords = c("start_lon", "start_lat"), crs = 4326) %>%
  st_transform(crs = "EPSG:2272") %>%
  st_join(PHLTracts %>% st_transform(crs = "EPSG:2272"), join = st_intersects, left = TRUE) %>%
  rename(Origin.Tract = GEOID) %>%
  mutate(start_lon = unlist(map(geometry, 1)),
         start_lat = unlist(map(geometry, 2))) %>%
  select(-geometry) %>%
  st_as_sf(coords = c("end_lon", "end_lat"), crs = 4326) %>%
  st_transform(crs = "EPSG:2272") %>%
  st_join(PHLTracts %>% st_transform(crs = "EPSG:2272"), join = st_intersects, left = TRUE) %>%
  rename(Destination.Tract = GEOID) %>%
  mutate(end_lon = unlist(map(geometry, 1)),
         end_lat = unlist(map(geometry, 2)))
}))

Processing Model Data

Create Space-Time Panel

In the following step, a full panel is created to summarize counts by station for each time interval. Fixed census tract level information, station-based locational features (distance to nearest high speed transit station and distance to nearest bike lane) and each stations geographic information (lat/lon) Is retained for joining later to other data.

study.panel <- 
  expand.grid(interval60=unique(dat_census$interval60), 
              start_station = unique(dat_census$start_station)) %>%
  left_join(., dat_census %>%
              select(start_station, Origin.Tract, 
                     start_lon, start_lat, bikenetwork_nn1, highspeed_nn1, schools_nn1)%>%
              distinct() %>%
              group_by(start_station) %>%
              slice(1))
ride.panel <- 
  dat_census %>%
  mutate(Trip_Counter = 1) %>%
  right_join(study.panel) %>% 
  group_by(interval60, start_station, Origin.Tract, start_lon, start_lat, 
           bikenetwork_nn1, highspeed_nn1, schools_nn1) %>% #amenities feature added here
  summarize(Trip_Count = sum(Trip_Counter, na.rm=T)) %>%
  left_join(weather.Panel) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  filter(is.na(start_station) == FALSE) %>%
  mutate(week = week(interval60),
         dotw = wday(interval60, label = TRUE)) %>%
  filter(is.na(Origin.Tract) == FALSE)

ride.panel <- 
  left_join(ride.panel, PHLCensus %>%
              as.data.frame() %>%
              select(-geometry), by = c("Origin.Tract" = "GEOID"))

Create Time Lags

Based on the pattern observed in the exploratory plots as well as the rebalancing plans aim, we created time lag variables using units of hours and days. Our hour-based lag variables range from one hour beforehand to 24 hours beforehand, while our day-based lag variables account from three days before a holiday to three days post a holiday.

Note that the only holiday in July, 2022 was Independence Day on July 4th (185th day of the year), to keep temporal cohesiveness, we split the data based on whether a trip occurred after or before week 29. Since holiday effect have to be accounted for by the training data (ride.Train), all data before week 29 is splitted into the training set.

ride.panel <- 
  ride.panel %>% 
  arrange(start_station, interval60) %>% 
  mutate(lagHour = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,1),
         lag2Hours = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,2),
         lag3Hours = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,3),
         lag4Hours = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,4),
         lag12Hours = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,12),
         lag1day = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,24),
         holiday = ifelse(yday(interval60) == 185,1,0)) %>%
   mutate(day = yday(interval60)) %>%
   mutate(holidayLag = case_when(dplyr::lag(holiday, 1) == 1 ~ "PlusOneDay",
                                 dplyr::lag(holiday, 2) == 1 ~ "PlustTwoDays",
                                 dplyr::lag(holiday, 3) == 1 ~ "PlustThreeDays",
                                 dplyr::lead(holiday, 1) == 1 ~ "MinusOneDay",
                                 dplyr::lead(holiday, 2) == 1 ~ "MinusTwoDays",
                                 dplyr::lead(holiday, 3) == 1 ~ "MinusThreeDays",
                                 TRUE ~ NA_character_))

ride.panel$holidayLag[is.na(ride.panel$holidayLag)] <- "0"

ride.Train <- filter(ride.panel, week < 29)
ride.Test <- filter(ride.panel, week >= 29)

Model Development

We trained a total of 6 models by gradually testing out more complex combinations of independent features against all records of hourly trip count on OLS regression. By comparing reg3, reg4, and reg5, and reg6, it is found that by accounting for temporal (lag) features, there are significant improvement in the models adjusted R-squared from 19.7% (reg3) to 30.0% (reg4) and 30.1% (reg5).

Between reg5 and reg6, however, it is observed that there is no observable improvement in the models adjusted R-squared, and that both locational (amenities) features are not significant. This suggests that the amenities influences have been perfectly accounted for by the station fixed effect.

reg1 <- 
  lm(Trip_Count ~  hour(interval60) + dotw + Temperature,  data=ride.Train)

reg2 <- 
  lm(Trip_Count ~  as.character(start_station) + dotw + Temperature,  data=ride.Train)

reg3 <- 
  lm(Trip_Count ~  as.character(start_station) + hour(interval60) + dotw + Temperature + Precipitation, 
     data=ride.Train)

reg4 <- 
  lm(Trip_Count ~  as.character(start_station) +  hour(interval60) + dotw + Temperature + Precipitation +
                   lagHour + lag2Hours +lag3Hours + lag12Hours + lag1day, 
     data=ride.Train)

reg5 <- 
  lm(Trip_Count ~  as.character(start_station) + hour(interval60) + dotw + Temperature + Precipitation +
                   lagHour + lag2Hours +lag3Hours +lag12Hours + lag1day + holidayLag + holiday, 
     data=ride.Train)

reg6 <- 
  lm(Trip_Count ~  as.character(start_station) + hour(interval60) + dotw + Temperature + Precipitation +
                   lagHour + lag2Hours +lag3Hours +lag12Hours + lag1day + holidayLag + holiday +
                   bikenetwork_nn1 + highspeed_nn1, #did not include schools since there's no correlation
     data=ride.Train)

Evaluating Model Performance

Predicting for Test Data

We then created a nested data frame of test data by week. Using the nested test dataset, we respectively used all 6 models to predict trips generated at each Indego station for each hour after week 29, and calculated the models mean absolute error (MAE) and the standard deviation of the models absolute error (ad_AE) by week 29, 30, and 31.

Since amenities features are perfectly collinear with the station fixed effect, reg6 is removed from the following steps of validation.

ride.Test.weekNest <- 
  ride.Test %>%
  nest(data = -week)

model_pred <- function(dat, fit){
   pred <- predict(fit, newdata = dat)}

week_predictions <- 
  ride.Test.weekNest %>% 
    mutate(ATime_FE = map(.x = data, fit = reg1, .f = model_pred),
           BSpace_FE = map(.x = data, fit = reg2, .f = model_pred),
           CTime_Space_FE = map(.x = data, fit = reg3, .f = model_pred),
           DTime_Space_FE_timeLags = map(.x = data, fit = reg4, .f = model_pred),
           ETime_Space_FE_timeLags_holidayLags = map(.x = data, fit = reg5, .f = model_pred)) %>% 
    gather(Regression, Prediction, -data, -week) %>%
    mutate(Observed = map(data, pull, Trip_Count),
           Absolute_Error = map2(Observed, Prediction,  ~ abs(.x - .y)),
           MAE = map_dbl(Absolute_Error, mean, na.rm = TRUE),
           sd_AE = map_dbl(Absolute_Error, sd, na.rm = TRUE))

Comparing Predictions by Different Models

Corresponding with the regression results, the following plot shows that the models have generally yielded improved performance when lag features are accounted for, since models D (model accounting for all everyday lag features) and E (model accounting for all everyday lag features and holiday lag features) generally perform significantly better than models A, B, and C which failed to account for lag features (fig.9). Limited by an absence of holiday in the test data, model D and model E generally match one another, however, in week 30, model E yields marginally higher mean absolute errors.

week_predictions %>%
  dplyr::select(week, Regression, MAE) %>%
  gather(Variable, MAE, -Regression, -week) %>%
  ggplot(aes(week, MAE)) + 
    geom_bar(aes(fill = Regression), position = "dodge", stat="identity") +
    scale_fill_manual(values = palette6) +
    labs(title = "Figure.9 Mean Absolute Errors by model specification and week") +
  plotTheme

The following plot of predicted and observed time series of bike share trips under each model for the entire test period (week 29 to 31 of July 2022) further confirms observations in the previous bar chart, revealing that predictions by model D, E, F are better matched with real-life observations (fig.10). Like the previous bar charts, however, the effect of holiday is not pronounced between model D and model E.

week_predictions %>% 
    mutate(interval60 = map(data, pull, interval60),
           start_station = map(data, pull, start_station)) %>%
    dplyr::select(interval60, start_station, Observed, Prediction, Regression) %>%
    unnest() %>%
    gather(Variable, Value, -Regression, -interval60, -start_station) %>%
    group_by(Regression, Variable, interval60) %>%
    summarize(Value = sum(Value)) %>%
    ggplot(aes(interval60, Value, colour=Variable)) + 
      geom_line(size = 1.1) + 
      facet_wrap(~Regression, ncol=1) +
      labs(title = "Figure.10 Predicted/Observed bike share time series", 
           subtitle = "Philadelphia; A test set of 3 weeks",  
           x = "Hour", y= "Station Trips") +
      plotTheme

Examining Final Model Performance

Accounting for model-based prediction plots and each models adjusted R-squared, we took model D as our final model and mapped its mean absolute errors by station (fig.11). By plotting for observed v. predicted trips for different time periods of the day during weekday and weekend, we find that the final model is under-predicting in general.

week_predictions %>%

                                 hour(interval60) >= 7 & hour(interval60) < 10 ~ "AM Rush",

  ggplot()+

By breaking down model MAE by different time periods of the day during weekday and weekend, we continue to see that the spatial pattern of error persists, with the highest MAE concentrating in and around Center City across all periods (fig.13). This heavily compromises our models utility, since those stations are most likely to be the busiest stations demanding best demand rebalancing strategies.

week_predictions %>% 
    mutate(interval60 = map(data, pull, interval60),
           start_station = map(data, pull, start_station), 
           start_lat = map(data, pull, start_lat), 
           start_lon = map(data, pull, start_lon),
           dotw = map(data, pull, dotw) ) %>%
    select(interval60, start_station, start_lon,

  filter(Regression == "DTime_Space_FE_timeLags")%>%

  summarize(MAE = mean(abs(Observed-Prediction), na.rm = TRUE))%>%
  ggplot(.)+
  geom_sf(data = PHLTracts, fill = "black")+

Finally, accounting for socio-economic and demographic features, we find that overall, the models MAE exhibits a negative correlation with public transit usage, whereas the models MAE exhibits a positive correlation with a census tracts median household income and share of white population (fig.14). These observations point to the fact that the model performance is restricted at the tract level, resulting in unresolved biases.

week_predictions %>% 
    mutate(interval60 = map(data, pull, interval60),
           start_station = map(data, pull, start_station), 
           start_lat = map(data, pull, start_lat), 
           start_lon = map(data, pull, start_lon),
           dotw = map(data, pull, dotw),
           Percent_Taking_Public_Trans = map(data, pull, Percent_Taking_Public_Trans),
           Med_Inc = map(data, pull, Med_Inc),
           Percent_White = map(data, pull, Percent_White)) %>%
    select(interval60, start_station, start_lon, 
           start_lat, Observed, Prediction, Regression,
           dotw, Percent_Taking_Public_Trans, Med_Inc, Percent_White) %>%
    unnest() %>%
  filter(Regression == "DTime_Space_FE_timeLags")%>%
  mutate(weekend = ifelse(dotw %in% c("Sun", "Sat"), "Weekend", "Weekday"),
         time_of_day = case_when(hour(interval60) < 7 | hour(interval60) > 18 ~ "Overnight",
                                 hour(interval60) >= 7 & hour(interval60) < 10 ~ "AM Rush",
                                 hour(interval60) >= 10 & hour(interval60) < 15 ~ "Mid-Day",
                                 hour(interval60) >= 15 & hour(interval60) <= 18 ~ "PM Rush")) %>%
  filter(time_of_day == "AM Rush") %>%
  group_by(start_station, Percent_Taking_Public_Trans, Med_Inc, Percent_White) %>%
  summarize(MAE = mean(abs(Observed-Prediction), na.rm = TRUE))%>%
  gather(-start_station, -MAE, key = "variable", value = "value")%>%
  ggplot(.)+
  geom_point(aes(x = value, y = MAE), alpha = 0.4)+

  facet_wrap(~variable, scales = "free")+

       y="Mean Absolute Error (Trips)")+
  plotTheme

Prediction Interpretation

In conclusion, our model has shown effort and progress to predict Indego bike share ridership volumes by tapping into primarily temporal (lag) features, with a combination of weather factors and station fixed-effect. With high statistical significance, lag features in the final model output provide valuable insights into how future ridership volume could be predicted between a few hours to several days, so that Indego bikes could be strategically re-balanced via both manual or virtual strategies.

Nonetheless, while the model demonstrates competitive fit with the overall city-wide trip volume, it still has limited generalizability, particularly among most frequently used stations around the Center City, as well as in census tracts with higher median household income and share of white population. These shortcomings would require additional refinement.
